Boil the potatoes: Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Place the @baby red potatoes{24%ounce} in a large #pot{} with @salt{large pinch} and enough water to cover them. Bring to a boil and cook for about ~{15%minutes}, until fork-tender. Drain and set aside.

Halve, peel, and mince the @shallot{2}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%clove}. Working one at a time, hold each @rosemary{1/4%ounce}(sprigs) at one end and pull in the opposite direction, to strip the leaves. Trim the long stem end of the @green beans{12%ounce}.

In a #medium bowl{}, soak the @white bread{2} with the @chicken stock concentrate{2} and @water{1/2%cup}. Break up the bread with your hands until a paste forms. Add the @ground beef{20%ounce}, shallots, half the garlic, half the rosemary, and a large pinch of @salt{1/2%teaspoon} and @pepper{1/2%teaspoon}. Mix with your hands until just combined.

Form the meatloaf mixture into four oval loaves and place on a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}. Place in the oven for about ~{20%minutes}, until cooked through. Toss the green beans on another baking sheet with a large drizzle of @olive oil{4%teaspoon} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast ~{10-12%minutes}, until shriveled.

In the same pot you cooked the potatoes in, heat @butter{2%tablespoon}, the remaining rosemary, and the remaining garlic over medium heat. Cook ~{30%seconds}, until melted and fragrant. Return the potatoes to the pot along with the @sour cream{4%tablespoon}. Mash with a #fork{} or #potato masher{} until creamy. Season generously with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Serve: Plate the rosemary mashed potatoes before topping with the roasted green beans and Tuscan meatloaf. Enjoy!

> We're not sure what we like best about this recipe: the flavorful herbs and spices in the ground meat, the fact that individual patties don't take nearly as long as traditional meatloaf to cook, or the silky, melt-in-your-mouth mashed potatoes. We'll let you (or your kids!) make the call.